a:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Nitric oxide’s role in mTOR overdrive—new or recycled insight?"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"TSC2 protein’s weakened brake may explain some autism pathways"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Hype vs. lab reality: where this fits in autism’s tangled research"}]]}]]}]}]
b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Autism research has a way of turning every molecular clue into a headline-grabbing 'breakthrough.' This week’s candidate: ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06573-9","children":"nitric oxide"}],", a humble signaling molecule, now accused of triggering a cellular chain reaction that might underpin ",["$","em",null,{"children":"some"}]," forms of autism. The study, ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2024/05/240515123412.htm","children":["published in ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Science"}]]}],", pins the blame on nitric oxide’s ability to disable TSC2, a protein that normally keeps the mTOR pathway—the cell’s growth and protein factory—in check. When TSC2 falters, mTOR goes into overdrive, a pattern already linked to neurodevelopmental disorders.\nThe mechanism itself isn’t entirely new. mTOR’s role in autism has been ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cell.com/neuron/fulltext/S0896-6273(15)00202-4","children":"studied for over a decade"}],", and nitric oxide’s signaling tricks are well-documented in other contexts. What’s different here is the ",["$","em",null,{"children":"cascade"}],": researchers mapped how a spike in nitric oxide doesn’t just tweak communication between neurons—it ",["$","em",null,{"children":"rewires"}]," the cell’s internal checks and balances. The question isn’t whether this happens (the data’s solid), but whether it’s a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"cause"}]," or a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"consequence"}]," of autism’s complexity.\nEarly reactions from the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.reddit.com/r/neuroscience/comments/1d5xy2z/nitric_oxide_and_autism_new_study_suggests/","children":"neuroscience community"}]," are cautiously intrigued. 'Interesting, but let’s not pretend we’ve found ",["$","em",null,{"children":"the"}]," switch,' notes one researcher on a technical forum. Another points out that mTOR inhibitors—drugs already in trials for autism—haven’t exactly been ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT02928661","children":"miracle cures"}],"."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/autisms-nitric-oxide-link-a-real-signal-or-just-no/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A molecular domino effect—or just another piece in a 1,000-piece puzzle?","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"A molecular domino effect—or just another piece in a 1,000-piece puzzle?"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The real tension here isn’t scientific—it’s strategic. This study lands in a field crowded with competing hypotheses: genetic mutations, synaptic pruning gone wrong, immune dysfunction. Nitric oxide’s role is elegant, but is it ",["$","em",null,{"children":"actionable"}],"? The mTOR pathway is a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6024610/","children":"notoriously tricky target"}],": too much inhibition stunts normal brain function, too little does nothing for symptoms. Pharma companies like ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.novartis.com/news/media-releases/novartis-reports-new-data-everolimus-autism-spectrum-disorder-associated-tuberous-sclerosis-complex","children":"Novartis"}]," and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.roche.com/media/releases/med-cor-2021-03-15","children":"Roche"}]," have poured millions into mTOR-related autism treatments, with mixed results. If nitric oxide is indeed a key upstream trigger, it could refocus those efforts—or just add another layer of complexity.\nFor developers and bioinformaticians, the open question is whether this mechanism is ","$L13"," to model. The study’s ","$L14"," suggests the nitric oxide-TSC2-mTOR axis is more of a ","$L15"," than a root cause, meaning it might explain variability in symptoms rather than origins. That’s useful, but it’s not the kind of clean target that excites investors or accelerates drug pipelines.\nThe broader signal? Autism research is inching toward a ","$L16"," of the condition—less a single broken pathway, more a system where small disruptions cascade unpredictably. Nitric oxide might be one of those disruptions. Or it might be a red herring in a field that’s had ","$L17","."]}]]}]
